=========================================================
MAXIMUM SUBARRAY - KADANE'S ALGORITHM EXPLANATION
=========================================================
C++ SOLUTION:
class Solution {
public:
    int maxSubArray(vector<int>& nums) {
        int max_sum = INT_MIN; // Keeps track of the best sum overall
        int current_sum = 0;   // Keeps track of the current window's sum
        
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            current_sum += nums[i];
            
            // Update max_sum if we found a new highest sum
            if (current_sum > max_sum) {
                max_sum = current_sum;
            }
            
            // If current_sum becomes negative, reset it.
            // It's not worth keeping this prefix for the next elements.
            if (current_sum < 0) {
                current_sum = 0;
            }
        }
        
        return max_sum;
    }
};
THE CORE IDEA
-------------
Instead of looking at every possible subarray (which takes too long), we walk through the array left to right, maintaining a "running sum" (curr). 

Rule 1: Add the current number to the running sum.
Rule 2: If the running sum is greater than our highest recorded sum (max), update 'max'.
Rule 3: If the running sum drops below 0, it means our current sequence is doing more harm than good. We throw it away by resetting the running sum to 0 and starting fresh with the next number.

EXAMPLE VISUALIZATION
---------------------
Let's trace the algorithm using LeetCode's standard example array:
Array: [-2,  1, -3,  4, -1,  2,  1, -5,  4]

Initial State:
curr = 0
max  = -Infinity

Step-by-step execution:

| Step | Num | curr (before check) | max updated? | curr drops < 0? | curr (end of step) |
|------|-----|---------------------|--------------|-----------------|--------------------|
|  1   | -2  | 0 + (-2) = -2       | max = -2     | YES. Reset to 0 | 0                  |
|  2   |  1  | 0 + 1 = 1           | max = 1      | No              | 1                  |
|  3   | -3  | 1 + (-3) = -2       | None         | YES. Reset to 0 | 0                  |
|  4   |  4  | 0 + 4 = 4           | max = 4      | No              | 4                  |
|  5   | -1  | 4 + (-1) = 3        | None         | No              | 3                  |
|  6   |  2  | 3 + 2 = 5           | max = 5      | No              | 5                  |
|  7   |  1  | 5 + 1 = 6           | max = 6      | No              | 6                  |
|  8   | -5  | 6 + (-5) = 1        | None         | No              | 1                  |
|  9   |  4  | 1 + 4 = 5           | None         | No              | 5                  |

Result: The variable 'max' holds the value 6, which is the sum of the subarray [4, -1, 2, 1].

THE JAVA CODE
-------------
class Solution {
    public int maxSubArray(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;
        int curr = 0;
        int max = Integer.MIN_VALUE; 
        
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            curr += nums[i];      // Rule 1
            
            if (curr > max) {     // Rule 2
                max = curr;
            }
            
            if (curr < 0) {       // Rule 3
                curr = 0;
            }
        }
        
        return max;
    }
}
